Comparing the BAIT and soundecology implementations of ACI

Setup

Loading the libraries and the data files.

Load BAIT ACI Data

Loads ACI values calculated on the BAIT tool.

bait_aci <- read.csv("aci_totals/ACI_0_49_1avg.CSV", header = FALSE)

Calculate ACI with soundecology

For every sound file (0.wav to 49.wav), the ACI value is computed.

The Amplitude Index is also computed. M is the median of the amplitude envelope of the sounds, effectively a measure of how loud the clip is. This is used later in the analysis.

aci <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = 5, nrow = 50))
names(aci) <- c("file", "file_number", "soundecology", "BAIT", "M")
aci$soundecology <- as.numeric(aci$soundecology)
aci$BAIT <- as.numeric(aci$BAIT)
aci$file_number <- as.numeric(0:49)

i <- 1

for (soundfile_name in paste0("SOUND/", 0:49, ".wav")) {
    soundfile <- readWave(soundfile_name)

    invisible(capture.output(ac <- acoustic_complexity(soundfile, min_freq = NA, 
        max_freq = NA, j = 5, fft_w = 256)))
    med <- M(soundfile)
    aci[i, ]$file <- soundfile_name
    aci[i, 3:5] <- c(ac$AciTotAll_left, bait_aci$V2[i], med)

    i <- i + 1
}

aci

Plot ACI values

Plot the ACI values calculated by BAIT and the soundecology package for each sound file side-by-side. There are notable differences between the calculations on the two platforms, though some are far closer than others. For example, the calcualtions for 0.wav, 7.wav, and 49.wav are relatively close, while the calculations for 6.wav, 17.wav, and 48.wav are wildly different (with the result from BAIT being much higher than the value returned by the soundecology package’s aci function).

aci_long_df <- aci[, 2:4] %>% pivot_longer(!file_number, names_to = "source", values_to = "aci")

p <- ggplot(aci_long_df, aes(fill = source, y = aci, x = file_number, na.rm = TRUE, 
    width = 0.75))
p <- p + geom_bar(position = "dodge", stat = "identity")

Differences between Soundecology and BAIT

ggscatter(aci, x = "soundecology", y = "BAIT")

There doesn’t appear to be a strong correlation between the ACI values calculated by the soundecology package and BAIT. However, if one looks at the waveforms of the sounds where the aci value calculated on soundecology and BAIT is very similar (the 3 plots on the left) and those where the value is very different (the 3 on the right), an obvious pattern is visible. It appears as though tracks with more sound1 end up with more similar values.

# png('/Users/davk/Documents/phd/writing/sbat-paper/images/aci_verification/waveforms.png',
# width = 210, height = 110, units = 'mm', res = 300)

# Create a plot
op <- par(mfrow = c(2, 3))

for (soundfile_name in paste0("SOUND/", c(0, 7, 49, 6, 17, 48), ".wav")) {
    soundfile <- readWave(soundfile_name)

    samples <- length(soundfile@left)
    rate <- soundfile@samp.rate

    timeArray <- (0:(samples - 1))/rate
    plot(timeArray, soundfile@left, type = "l", col = "black", xlab = "Time (ms)", 
        ylab = "Amplitude", yaxt = "n", ylim = c(-25000, 25000), main = soundfile_name)
}

par(op)

# Close the png file dev.off()

Examining plots of the difference between the ACI values from BAIT and soundecology and a plot of the average amplitude of each of the files, there appears to be a relationship.

op <- par(mfrow = c(2, 1))

pct_diff <- data.frame(file = 0:49, diff = (aci$BAIT - aci$soundecology)/aci$BAIT)
diff_plot <- ggplot(pct_diff, aes(y = diff, x = file, na.rm = TRUE)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge", 
    stat = "identity") + labs(title = "Difference between BAIT ACI and soundecology ACI", 
    x = "#.wav", y = "BAIT-soundecology")

M_plot <- ggplot(aci, aes(y = M, x = 0:49, na.rm = TRUE)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge", 
    stat = "identity") + labs(title = "Average amplitude of test sound files", x = "#.wav", 
    y = "average amplitude")

ggarrange(diff_plot, M_plot, nrow = 2)

Data are not normally distributed, so we use Spearman’s Rank correlation.

M_diff <- data.frame(file = 0:49, M = aci$M, diff = pct_diff$diff)

cor.test(M_diff$M, M_diff$diff, method = "spearman")
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  M_diff$M and M_diff$diff
## S = 40598, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##        rho 
## -0.9494838

And plot the results in a scatterplot with a regression line.

library("ggpubr")
ggscatter(M_diff, x = "M", y = "diff", add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, cor.coef = TRUE, 
    cor.method = "spearman", xlab = "M", ylab = "BAIT ACI vs soundecology ACI")

Conclusion

The test shows a strong negative correlation, meaning that the larger difference in computed ACI values occurs in conjunction with quieter sounds. The can likely be attributed to difference in precision (BAIT uses single-precision 16-bit floating point math). Quieter sounds - those with lower median amplitudes - produce smaller values in an FFT. These smaller signals amplify the precision errors that arise due to the 16-bit operation of the microcontroller, leading to greater differences in the final ACI calculation.

  1. “More sound” is pretty ill-defined, but a higher average amplitude is what we end up using to measure this.↩
